<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Grammys-List, Adv 26-28-2nd Add,1127</SECOND>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: of Confusion.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ BEST ARRANGEMENT ON AN INSTRUMENTAL: Jorge Calandrelli, ``Any
Time, Any Season''; Dave Grusin, ``The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter'';
Patrick Williams, ``Jive Samba''; Michael Convertino, ``Main
Title''; Bill Holman, ``Take the `A' Train.''
   _ BEST INSTRUMENTAL ARRANGEMENT ACCOMPANYING VOCAL: Frank
Foster, ``Deedles' Blues'' (from ``Diane Schuur &amp; the Count Basie
Orchestra''); Jack Walrath, ``I'm So Lonesome I Could Cry'' (from
``Master of Suspense''; Henry Mancini, ``It Might As Well Be
Spring'' (from ``The Hollywood Musicals''); Randy Kerber, ``Over
the Rainbow'' (from ``One Voice''); Van Dyke Parks and Bill Ginn,
``A Singer Must Die'' (from ``Famous Blue Raincoat'').
   _ BEST ALBUM PACKAGE (ART DIRECTORS): Ron Scarselli,
``Document''; Joe Stelmach, ``Duke Ellington: The Webster-Blanton
Band''; Bruce Licher, ``Echelons''; Bill Johnson, ``King's Record
Shop''; Peter Barrett, ``Shaka Zulu.''
   _ BEST ALBUM NOTES: Charles K. Wolfe, ``The Bristol Sessions'';
Peter Guralnick, ``The Complete Sun Sessions''; Nolan Porterfield,
``Jimmie Rodgers on Record: America's Blue Yodeler''; Mark Tucker,
``Singers and Soloists of the Swing Bands''; Orrin Keepnews,
``Thelonious Monk _ The Complete Riverside Recordings.''
   _ BEST HISTORICAL ALBUM (PRODUCERS): Kyle Young, ``The Bristol
Sessions''; Paul Tannen, ``The Gershwin Collection''; Kim Cooke and
Bob Porter, ``The Otis Redding Story''; Margaret Robinson,
``Singers and Soloists of the Swing Bands''; Orrin Keepnews,
``Thelonious Monk _ The Complete Riverside Recordings.''
   _ BEST ENGINEERED RECORDING _ NON-CLASSICAL (ENGINEERS): Bruce
Swedien, ``Bad''; Don Murray and Keith Grant, ``Cinemagic''; Ben
Harris, Kyle Lehning and Joe Bogen, ``Heart and Soul''; Andrew
Jackson, ``A Momentary Lapse of Reason''; Tom Jung, ``Neon''; Al
Schmitt, ``Reflections.''
   _ PRODUCER OF THE YEAR (NON-CLASSICAL): Emilio and The Jerks;
Quincy Jones and Michael Jackson; Daniel Lanois and Brian Eno; John
Mellencamp and Don Gehman; Narada Michael Walden.
   _ BEST CLASSICAL ALBUM: Edo De Waart conducting the San
Francisco Symphony, ``Adams: The Chairman Dances@Christian Zeal and
Activity@Two Fanfares for Orchestra@Tromba Iontana@Short Ride in a
Fast Machine@Common Tones in Simple Time''; Sir Georg Solti
conducting the Chicago Symphony Orchestra, ``Beethoven: Symphony
No. 9 in D Minor''; Robert Shaw conducting the Atlanta Symphony
Chorus and Orchestra, ``Faure: Requiem, Op. 48, Durufle: Requiem,
Op. 9''; Leonard Slatkin conducting the St. Louis Symphony and
Elmar Oliveira, ``Hanson: Symphony No. 2 (Romantic)@ Barber: Violin
Concerto''; Vladimir Horowitz, ``Horowitz in Moscow.''
   _ BEST ORCHESTRAL RECORDING: Sir Georg Solti conducting the
Chicago Symphony Orchestra, ``Beethoven: Symphony No. 9 in D
Minor''; James Levine conducting the Berlin Philharmonic, ``Berg,
Webern, Schoenberg: Orchestral Pieces''; Leonard Bernstein
conducting the New York Philharmonic, ``Copland: Symphony No.
3@Quiet City''; Leonard Slatkin conducting the St. Louis Symphony,
``Hanson: Symphony No. 2 (Romantic)''; Charles Dutoit conducting
the Montreal Symphony Orchestra, ``Holst: The Planets.''
   _ BEST OPERA RECORDING: Sir Georg Solti conducting the Vienna
Philharmonic Orchestra and Chorus, ``Mozart: Die Entfuhrung Aus Dem
Serail''; Herbert von Karajan conducting the Berlin Philharmonic
Orchestra and Chorus, ``Mozart: Don Giovanni''; Riccardo Muti
conducting the Vienna Philharmonic and Chorus, ``Mozart: The
Marriage of Figaro''; James Levine conducting the Vienna
Philharmonic, ``Strauss: Ariadne Auf Naxos''; Riccardo Chailly
conducting the Orchestra and Coro del Teatro Communale di Bologna,
``Verdi: Macbeth.''
   _ BEST CHORAL PERFORMANCE (OTHER THAN OPERA): John Eliot
Gardiner conducting The Monteverdi Choir and The English Baroque
Soloists, ``Bach: St. John Passion''; Michael Tilson Thomas
conducting the Mormon Tabernacle Choir and Utah Symphony,
``Copland: Old American Songs; Canticle of Freedom; Four Motets'';
Robert Shaw conducting the Atlanta Symphony Chorus and Orchestra,
``Hindemith: When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd (A Requiem
for Those We Love''; Sir Charles Mackerras conducting the Prague
Philharmonic Chorus and Czech Philharmonic Orchestra, ``Janacek:
Glagolitic Mass''; Klaus Tennstedt conducting the London
Philharmonic Choir and Orchestra, ``Mahler: Symphony No. 8 in E
Flat''; Andre Previn conducting the Brighton Festival Chorus and
Royal Philharmonic Orchestra, ``Tippett: A Child of Our Time.''
   _ BEST CLASSICAL PERFORMANCE _ INSTRUMENTAL SOLOIST OR SOLISTS
(WITH ORCHESTRA): Elmar Oliveira (Leonard Slatkin cond. St. Louis
Symphony), ``Barber: Violin Concerto, Op. 14''; Murray Perahia
(Bernard Haitink cond. Concertgebouw Orchestra), ``Beethoven: Piano
Concerto No. 5 in E Flat (Emperor)''; Wynton Marsalis (Donald
Hunsberger cond. Eastman Wind Ensemble), ``Carnaval (works by
Arban, Clarke, Levy, Paganini, Rimsky-Korsakov, Bellstedt''; Dale
Clevenger (Franz Lizst Chamber Orchestra), ``Mozart: Horn Concertos
No. 1-4, Rondo, Fragment''; Itzhak Perlman (James Levine cond.
Vienna Philharmonic), ``Mozart: Violin Concertos Nos. 2 in D@4 in
D.''
   _ BEST CLASSICAL PERFORMANCE _ INSTRUMENTAL SOLOIST OR SOLOISTS
(WITHOUT ORCHESTRA): Andras Schiff, piano, ``Bach: The
Well-Tempered Clavier, Book 2''; Murray Perahia, ``Beethoven: Piano
Sonatas No. 17, Op. 31@18, Op. 31@26, Op. 81A''; Vladimir Horowitz,
piano, ``Horowitz in Moscow''; Itzhak Perlman, violin (Samuel
Sanders, accomp.), ``Kreisler: My Favorite Kreisler''; Peter
Serkin, piano, ``Stravinsky: Wolpe: Lieberson (Stravinsky: Serenade
in A &amp; Sonata@Wolpe: Form IV: Broken Sequences, Pastorale,
Passacaglia@Lieberson: Bagatelles).
   _ BEST CHAMBER MUSIC PERFORMANCE (INSTRUMENTAL OR VOCAL): Itzhak
Perlman, Lynn Harrell &amp; Vladimir Ashkenazy, ``Beethoven: The
Complete Piano Trios''; Murray Perahia &amp; Members of the Amadeus
Quartet, ``Brahms: Piano Quartet No. 1 in G Minor''; Beaux Arts
Trio, ``Dvorak: Piano Trio in E Minor (Dumky)@ Mendelssohn: Piano
Trio in D Minor''; Jean-Pierre Rampal, Isaac Stern, Salvatore
Accardo, Mstislav Rostropovich, ``Mozart: The Flute Quartets (K.
285, 285A, 285B, 298)''; Kronos Quartet, ``White Man Sleeps (Music
by Volans, Ives, Hassell, Coleman, Johnston, Bartok).''
   _ BEST CLASSICAL VOCAL SOLOIST PERFORMANCE: Marni Nixon (Keith
Clark cond. Members of The Pacific Symphony Orchestra), ``Copland:
Eight Poems of Emily Dickinson''; Kathleen Battle (James Levine,
accomp.), ``Kathleen Battle _ Salzburg Recital (Faure, Handel,
Mendelssohn, Mozart, Purcell, Strauss, Spirituals)''; Elly Ameling
(Rudolf Jansen, accomp.), ``Soiree Francaise (Debussy, Faure,
Poulenc, Franck, Canteloube, Roussel, Chausson, Messiaen, etc.)'';
Jessye Norman (Geoffrey Parson, accomp.), ``(R.) Strauss: Lieder
Including `Malven'''; Arleen Augur (The Yale Cellos of Aldo
Parisot), ``Villa-Lobos: Bachianas Brasileiras No. 5 (for Soprano &amp;
Orchestra of Violincellos).''
   _ BEST CONTEMPORARY COMPOSITION: John Adams, ``Adams: The
Chairman Dances''; Milton Babbit, ``Babbit: Piano Concerto'';
Krzysztof Penderecki, ``Penderecki: Cello Concerto No. 2''; Joseph
Schwantner, ``Schwantner: A Sudden Rainbow''; Roger Sessions,
``Sessions: Symphony No. 5''; Michael Tippitt, ``Tippitt: The Mask
of Time.''
   _ BEST ENGINEERED RECORDING, CLASSICAL: Beethoven: Symphony No.
9 in D Minor (Sir Georg Solti cond. Chicago Symphony Orchestra;
Solos), John Pellowe, engineer; Faure: Requiem, Op. 48@Durufle:
Requiem, Op. 9 (Robert Shaw cond. Atlanta Symphony Orchestra &amp;
Chorus; Solos), Jack Renner, engineer; Hindemith: When Lilacs Last
in the Dooryard Bloom'd (A Requeim for Those We Love) (Robert Shaw
cond. Atlanta Symphony Orchestra & Chorus; Solos), Jack Renner,
engineer; Horowitz in Moscow (Vladimir Horowitz), Thomas Frost,
engineer; Tchaikovsky: 1812 Overture@Romeo &amp; Juliet@The Nutcracker
Suite (Sir Georg Solti cond. Chicago Symphony Orchestra), John
Pellowe, Engineer.
   _ CLASSICAL PRODUCER OF THE YEAR: Steven Epstein; Thomas Frost;
Michael Haas; Jay David Saks; Robert Woods.
